{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500840"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1685"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1685"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.2,0.24,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100038"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1685"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82430"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15928"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100038"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no symptoms such as chest pain, palpitations, dyspnoea, nausea, vomiting or muscle weakness. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His regular medications are gliclazide and candesartan. He is active, walking one kilometre daily and tending to his garden.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Physical examination is unremarkable. A random blood glucose is 6.6 mmol/L. Routine blood tests taken three hours prior to his appointment were all normal, except for a potassium of 7.4 mmol/L (3.6-5.0). An electrocardiogram shows normal sinus rhythm with no other changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat blood test","Emergency department referral","Administer calcium gluconate","Prescribe furosemide","No further action required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in this scenario is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat the blood test\u003C/strong\u003E. The reported potassium level of 7.4 mmol/L is likely spurious, given the patient\u0027s clinical presentation and lack of symptoms typically associated with severe hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this abnormal result is difficulty in blood sample collection leading to haemolysis. Haemolysis causes spurious hyperkalaemia by releasing intracellular potassium from ruptured red blood cells into the serum, falsely elevating the serum potassium levels. Haemolysis during sample collection or processing is a common cause of spurious hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of clinical correlation when interpreting laboratory results. The patient is clinically well, with no symptoms of hyperkalaemia such as muscle weakness or cardiac arrhythmias. His ECG is normal, which would be unusual with a true potassium level of 7.4 mmol/L. While he is taking an angiotensin II receptor blocker (candesartan) which can cause hyperkalaemia, it\u0027s unlikely to cause such a high level without accompanying symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency department referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overreaction to this single abnormal result in an otherwise well patient. It\u0027s important to verify the result before initiating any urgent interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering calcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the acute management of severe hyperkalaemia with ECG changes. Itis not appropriate in this case where the patient is asymptomatic and the ECG is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E, while it can help lower potassium levels, is not appropriate without confirming the hyperkalaemia, especially in an asymptomatic patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action required\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate, as the reported potassium level, if accurate, would represent a potentially life-threatening condition that requires investigation and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn such situations, the most prudent approach is to repeat the blood test to confirm the result before initiating any treatment or urgent referrals. This approach balances patient safety with avoiding unnecessary interventions based on potentially erroneous laboratory data.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A reported abnormal result in a routine laboratory investigation should not be taken at face value in a well, symptom-free patient.","Spurious hyperkalaemia can occur due to haemolysis during blood sample collection or processing.","Clinical correlation is essential when interpreting laboratory results, especially in asymptomatic patients."],"references":["Depret F, Peacock WF, Liu KD, et al. Management of hyperkalemia in the acutely ill patient. Ann Intensive Care 2019; 9:32"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1685"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82430"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T21:16:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T21:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1685"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100038"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/197"},"attribu